diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can damage any part of the body, including skin, joints, and/or organs inside the body.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of inadequately treated strep throat or scarlet fever, affecting the heart, joints, skin, and brain.

diagnoses.name: Infective Endocarditis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the inner lining of the heart chambers and heart valves, typically caused by bacteria.

diagnoses.name: Viral Myocarditis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the heart muscle, often due to a viral infection.

diagnoses.name: Acute Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints, leading to inflammation and joint deformities.

diagnoses.name: Septic Arthritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of a joint caused by infection, usually bacterial.

diagnoses.name: Disseminated Gonococcal Infection
diagnoses.description: A systemic infection caused by the bacterium Neisseria gonorrhoeae, which can involve joints and skin.

diagnoses.name: Adult-Onset Still's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare inflammatory disorder characterized by fever, rash, and joint pain, which may lead to chronic arthritis.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: A potentially serious infectious bacterial disease that mainly affects the lungs but can also affect other parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by Borrelia bacteria, spread by ticks. Can affect the skin, joints, heart, and nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of your body. It's characterized by symptoms like fatigue, joint pain, skin rashes, and fevers. Lymphadenopathy and ulcers can be associated symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. Symptoms include mouth sores, genital sores, eye inflammation, and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that originates in the lymphatic system, leading to lymphadenopathy, weight loss, fever, and night sweats.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: A virus that attacks the immune system. If left untreated, it can lead to AIDS. Symptoms include swollen lymph nodes, fever, weight loss, and sores in the mouth or genital area.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic disorder characterized by high blood sugar levels over a prolonged period. Symptoms may include frequent urination, increased thirst, and increased hunger. It can lead to hypoglycemia, especially in improperly managed cases.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.description: A sexually transmitted infection caused by the bacterium Treponema pallidum. Symptoms are divided into stages, including sores, skin rashes, fever, swollen lymph nodes, and mood changes.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, primarily the lungs and lymph glands. Symptoms include fatigue, lymphadenopathy, fever, weight loss, and skin lesions.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that causes inflammation of the digestive tract, which can lead to abdominal pain, severe diarrhea, fatigue, weight loss, and malnutrition. Ulcers and mouth sores are common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. Associated symptoms can include fatigue, fever, and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Insulinoma
diagnoses.description: A rare tumor of the pancreas that produces excess insulin, leading to hypoglycemia. Symptoms may include sweating, hunger, tremor, and confusion.

diagnoses: Connective tissue diseases (e.g., lupus, rheumatoid arthritis)
Hashimoto's Thyroiditis with fluctuating thyroid function
Type 1 Diabetes with associated thyroid autoimmunity (Autoimmune Polyglandular Syndrome)

diagnoses.name: Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy
diagnoses.description: A temporary heart condition that shares many of the symptoms of a heart attack, triggered by intense emotional or physical stress.

diagnoses.name: Osteoporosis
diagnoses.description: A disease that weakens bones, making them fragile and more likely to break.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Back Pain
diagnoses.description: Long-standing pain in the back that can be due to various causes, including musculoskeletal issues, disc degeneration, or underlying conditions like arthritis.

diagnoses.name: Dysgeusia
diagnoses.description: A distorted sense of taste, often causing a persistent unpleasant taste.

diagnoses.name: Otitis Externa
diagnoses.description: An inflammation or infection of the outer ear canal, often referred to as swimmer's ear.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin D Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Lack of adequate vitamin D, which can contribute to osteoporosis and has been associated with chronic pain conditions.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: A variety of disorders characterized by excessive worrying, nervousness, or fear that can trigger conditions like Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: A mood disorder that causes a persistent feeling of sadness and loss of interest and can exacerbate chronic pain conditions.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition that causes pain all over the body, which could relate to chronic back pain and dysgeusia due to its associated neuropathies.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic condition characterized by high blood sugar levels, which can lead to osteoporosis and contribute to dysgeusia.

diagnoses: Hypertensive heart disease with chronic kidney disease

diagnoses: Asthma (exacerbation triggered by an allergic reaction)

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by severe head pain accompanied by visual disturbances, nausea, and sensitivity to sound.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it temporarily blocks blood flow to the brain, causing symptoms similar to a stroke.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, causing brain cells to die.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves, causing symptoms like paresthesia.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, including possibly loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the fluid and membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord, often leading to headaches, fever, and a stiff neck.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain, which can cause various neurological symptoms depending on its location.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine characterized primarily by dizziness, vertigo, and imbalance, in addition to or in lieu of the typical migraine headache.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by a very low level of blood sugar (glucose), which can lead to symptoms like visual disturbances, confusion, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Hypertensive Crisis
diagnoses.description: A severe increase in blood pressure that can lead to a stroke. Symptoms may include severe headache, nausea, and visual disturbances.
